{
  "doc_id": "43982",
  "text": "Hyperglycemia at the time of cerebral ischemia leads to enhanced lactate and H + production, leading to intra-and extracellular acidosis [CITATION_1] concomitant with increased cerebral ischemic damage beyond the \"lactate threshold\" [CITATION_2] . Acidosis contributes to cerebral ischemia-induced brain damage by affecting multiple mechanisms including mitochondrial cell death pathways. Acidic pH is associated with loss of activity of mitochondrial electron transport chain complexes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The degree of enzyme activity loss was correlated with the severity of acidosis, and different electron transport chain complexes had different labilities to acidic pH [CITATION_5] . This study suggests decreased energy production during acidosis. On the other hand, acidosis is suggested to decrease the rate of ATP hydrolysis, which may be beneficial during ischemia / reperfusion when energy demand is high [CITATION_6] . Acidosis is shown to lower mitochondrial calcium buffering capacity [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Lowered extracellular pH results in depolarization of intrasynaptosomal mitochondria and increased oxidative stress in isolated rat brain synaptosomes [CITATION_9] . The acid-sensing ion channel 1a (ASIC1a) mediates acidosisinduced neuronal injury in several pathophysiological conditions is present on the plasma membrane as well as in mitochondria [CITATION_10] . ASIC1a is suggested to play a role in regulation of mitochondrial permeability transition pores [CITATION_11] . The literature suggests that the deleterious effects of acidosis on mitochondrial function are much outweighed by its beneficial effects, further supporting the participation of acidosis in brain damage following cerebral ischemia in hyperglycemic conditions. Testing efficacy of pharmacological agent that buffer intra-ischemic pH in animal models of diabetes may help design novel therapeutic approach to lower cerebral ischemic damage in diabetics.",
